1
00:00:02,140 --> 00:00:05,930
Reinforcement learning is
an exciting set of technologies.

2
00:00:05,930 --> 00:00:10,386
In fact, when I was working on my
PhD thesis reinforcement learning

3
00:00:10,386 --> 00:00:12,360
was the subject of my thesis.

4
00:00:12,360 --> 00:00:15,533
So I was and
still am excited about these ideas.

5
00:00:15,533 --> 00:00:20,896
Despite all the research momentum and
excitement behind reinforcement learning

6
00:00:20,896 --> 00:00:25,644
though, I think there is a bit or
maybe sometimes a lot of hype around it.

7
00:00:25,644 --> 00:00:31,354
So what I hope to do is share with you
a practical sense of where reinforcement

8
00:00:31,354 --> 00:00:35,919
learning is today in terms of
his utility for applications.

9
00:00:35,919 --> 00:00:40,889
One of the reasons for some of the hype
about reinforcement learning is, it turns

10
00:00:40,889 --> 00:00:45,657
out many of the research publications
have been on simulated environments.

11
00:00:45,657 --> 00:00:50,036
And having worked in both simulations and
on real robots myself,

12
00:00:50,036 --> 00:00:54,971
I can tell you that it's much easier
to get a reinforcement learning album

13
00:00:54,971 --> 00:00:59,940
to work in a simulation or
in a video game than in a real robot.

14
00:00:59,940 --> 00:01:04,788
So a lot of developers have commented
that even after they got it to work in

15
00:01:04,788 --> 00:01:08,763
simulation, it turned out to
be surprisingly challenging

16
00:01:08,763 --> 00:01:13,340
to get something to work in
the real world or the real robot.

17
00:01:13,340 --> 00:01:16,776
And so if you apply these
algorithms to a real application,

18
00:01:16,776 --> 00:01:21,449
this is one limitation that I hope you pay
attention to to make sure what you do does

19
00:01:21,449 --> 00:01:23,740
work on the real application.

20
00:01:23,740 --> 00:01:27,771
Second, despite all the media coverage
about reinforcement learning,

21
00:01:27,771 --> 00:01:32,519
today there are far fewer applications of
reinforcement learning than supervised and

22
00:01:32,519 --> 00:01:34,440
unsupervised learning.

23
00:01:34,440 --> 00:01:37,178
So if you are building
a practical application,

24
00:01:37,178 --> 00:01:39,983
the odds that you will find
supervised learning or

25
00:01:39,983 --> 00:01:43,389
unsupervised learning useful or
the right tool for the job,

26
00:01:43,389 --> 00:01:48,540
is much higher than the odds that you
would end up using reinforcement learning.

27
00:01:48,540 --> 00:01:53,070
I have used reinforcement learning a few
times myself especially on robotic control

28
00:01:53,070 --> 00:01:57,341
applications, but in my day to day applied
work, I end up using supervising and

29
00:01:57,341 --> 00:01:59,151
supervised learning much more.

30
00:02:00,240 --> 00:02:04,443
There is a lot of exciting research
in reinforcement learning right now,

31
00:02:04,443 --> 00:02:07,630
and I think the potential of
reinforcement learning for

32
00:02:07,630 --> 00:02:10,139
future applications is very large.

33
00:02:10,139 --> 00:02:14,688
And reinforcement learning still
remains one of the major pillars of

34
00:02:14,688 --> 00:02:16,028
machine learning.

35
00:02:16,028 --> 00:02:20,528
And so having it as a framework as
you develop your own machine learning

36
00:02:20,528 --> 00:02:24,953
algorithms, I hope will make you
more effective at building working

37
00:02:24,953 --> 00:02:27,840
machine learning systems as well.

38
00:02:27,840 --> 00:02:32,764
So I hope you've enjoyed this week's
materials on reinforcement learning, and

39
00:02:32,764 --> 00:02:37,940
specifically I hope you have fun getting
the lunar lander to land for yourself.

40
